What’s in our range nooks?!
Our range is Italian plaster and the nooks were built in to store what Chris likes to use most. It varies slightly from time of year, but mostly you’ll find:

(right side) cooking olive oil; butchers twine; spice spoons; finishing olive oil; allspice powder; turmeric powder; cumin powder; (left side) measuring cups; honey; pepper mill; finishing salts; smoked sweet paprika; garlic powder; ground cinnamon. And a Polaroid of us on Thanksgiving cooking in our dream kitchen. 🫶 #cljxstofferkitchen

You know that feeling, when you freshly paint something, and you stand back to see it for the first time, and you “love it!”?? But then there’s a little (or sometimes big) pit in your stomach because something is off. However, you just went through so much to get that color on the wall so you just keep saying you love it like you believe it because, honestly, you almost do. Objectively, it looks good! 

This color, the third time repainting this room, was the FIRST TIME, the pit wasn’t there in this space. It was meant to be. I fought going dark green, because I guess don’t I always go dark green?? And I’m so glad I stopped fighting it. It feels like a tone that has grown with me through so many homes and iterations and now, here, it feels familiar but fresh. I LOVE IT—truly truly. 

COLOR: @benjaminmoore Topsoil in a high gloss finish
Dark green and glossy ftw. All the details about what paint we used to get this ultra wet effect today on chrislovesjulia.com. #cljstudy

My living room got her colors tested, and she’s a Fall Girly through and through.

Here, I just got done zhushing our living room for fall and Andi was testing lighting for photos. When I looked at the batch, I realized I may not look super excited in these photos, but I remember feeling very fulfilled with the work I had just completed. There's fun and enjoyable parts about every job and for me and this job, it's all the hands-on creative stuff. It's the tinkering with decor and diving deep into designing a space. Moving a coffee table book to a different stack so the colors line up better. Figuring out undertones and painting a new space and revealing it in real time on stories. 

I've been doing this for soooo long. I have hundreds of photos of myself in many different spaces in many different houses, at many different ages (I started when I was 23!). And with each one, I see the peace in my eyes that I'm doing something that adds a little beauty to our family's world.

Orange Cranberry Sorbet:
1/2 cup cranberry sauce
Mandarin oranges in light syrup to the fill line

Banana Eggnog Ice Cream:
1 cup sliced banana
1/3 cup half and half
Eggnog to the fill line

Freeze overnight. Sorbet on the sorbet setting, stir then remix. Ice cream in ice cream setting, stir then remix.
